////very good advanced pointer qualifier question

///////////
#include <stdio.h>
        void foo(int *const *p);
        int main()
        {
            int i = 11;
            int *p = &i;
            foo(&p);
            printf("%d ", *p);
        }
        void foo(int *const *p)
        {
            int j = 10;
            *p = &j;
            printf("%d ", **p);
        }
        
///////////////////////////
It tests:
1.pointer-to-pointer
2.const placement meaning
3.dangling pointer bug
4.what you are allowed to modify vs not

void foo(int *const *p);   in this line
p          → pointer
*p         → pointer to int (int *)
*const     → this pointer cannot be changed

So:
👉 p points to a const pointer to int

Meaning:
Expression	Allowed?	Why
*p = something	❌ Not allowed	because *p is const pointer
**p = value	✔ Allowed	value of int can change
p = something	✔ Allowed	local pointer itself can change
🚨 Problem in Your Code

Inside foo():

int j = 10;
*p = &j;      // ❌ illegal

Why illegal?

Because:
*p  is  int *const

That means:
👉 pointer stored in caller (p in main) cannot be reassigned

Compiler should complain:
assignment of read-only location '*p'
⚠️ EVEN IF FORCED (very important)

Suppose compiler allowed it (some don’t strictly block).

Then:
p in main → now points to j
But j is local to foo().

After return:
j destroyed
p becomes dangling pointer

So final print:
printf("%d", *p);

👉 Undefined behaviour
👉 may print garbage
👉 may crash

✅ Correct Version (Safe)

If goal is to modify value:

#include <stdio.h>
void foo(int *const *p);
int main()
{
    int i = 11;
    int *p = &i;

    foo(&p);

    printf("%d ", *p);
}
void foo(int *const *p)
{
    **p = 10;   // modify value, not pointer
    printf("%d ", **p);
}
🎯 Output (Correct Version)
10 10

